newsitem.title: CHINA: Shanghai soybean futures end mixed.
newsitem.headline: Shanghai soybean futures end mixed.

text.p: Shanghai soybean futures ended mixed on Friday with early-maturing contracts rising on a technical correction while later-maturing contracts fell on long-term poor fundamentals, traders said.
The key January 1997 contract ended at an intra-day high of 3,135 yuan ($377) per tonne, rising 10 yuan. It opened at 3,130 and hit a low of 3,112.
March rose four to 3,090, May 18 to 3,218, July fell 36 to 3,255, September 12 to 3,376 and November one to 3,397.
Combined volume rose to 20,300 tonnes from 17,100.

Traders said successive falls in early-maturing contracts triggered short-covering today, while expectations of a good domestic harvest and more imports made many investors wary about the long-term trend.
"It was a technical correction after continuous losses in the past few days," one trader said. "But poor sentiment remained cautious with fundamentals little improved."
Traders expect soybeans to move in a narrow range in the next few days.
